{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488254","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488254"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:34:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:34:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"394"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"394","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/394"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.33,0.02,0.04,0.55]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"394"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111580"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"394","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/394"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"394"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93675"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"147"},{"type":"tags","id":"272"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2280"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"6511"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11447"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11448"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13668"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34009"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35518"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35653"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35654"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41831"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42072"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43004"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111580","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111580"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with an eight-hour history of right-sided pleuritic chest pain. The pain came on suddenly after a bout of coughing. He has no other symptoms and is not short of breath. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He is an active smoker with a 20 pack-year history. On examination, he appears well with pulse rate 80/min, blood pressure 114/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There is increased resonance on percussion on the right side of the chest, with reduced breath sounds at the apex. Previous pulmonary function tests from two years ago showed normal spirometry values with forced expiratory volume in one second 3.2 L (3.0-4.2) and forced vital capacity 4.1 L (3.8-5.2). A chest X-ray shows the pleural line 0.5 cm from the chest wall edge on the right. The patient has been in the Emergency Department for two hours and is now symptom-free.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Needle aspiration","Discharge home with repeat X-ray in two weeks","Continuous positive airway pressure","Intercostal drain insertion","Observe for four to six hours"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a primary spontaneous pneumothorax. The distinction between primary and secondary spontaneous pneumothorax is crucial for management decisions. Primary spontaneous pneumothorax occurs in patients without underlying lung disease, whilst secondary pneumothorax occurs in those with pre-existing lung pathology such as chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, cystic fibrosis, or interstitial lung disease. This patient\u0027s normal pulmonary function tests from two years ago (with forced expiratory volume in one second and forced vital capacity both within normal ranges) indicate he does not have chronic obstructive pulmonary disease despite his smoking history. Therefore, this is classified as a primary spontaneous pneumothorax.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObserve for four to six hours\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management. Current evidence supports observation for stable patients with primary spontaneous pneumothorax regardless of size. After this observation period, a repeat chest X-ray would be performed. If this demonstrates stability of the pneumothorax and the patient remains asymptomatic, discharge home with instructions to return if symptoms develop is appropriate. Follow-up with chest X-rays every 24-72 hours until near resolution is recommended.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeedle aspiration\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated for patients with developing symptoms or enlarging pneumothorax. As this patient is now asymptomatic with a stable pneumothorax, aspiration is not indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDischarge home with repeat X-ray in two weeks\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate without first observing the patient and obtaining a repeat chest X-ray to ensure stability. Additionally, follow-up should be more frequent initially (24-72 hours) rather than two weeks later.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinuous positive airway pressure\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in patients with a pneumothorax. The increased airway pressure can worsen a pneumothorax and potentially convert it to a tension pneumothorax.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntercostal drain insertion\u003C/strong\u003E is warranted in patients who are unstable or in whom conservative management has failed. Previous guidelines recommended intercostal drainage for large pneumothoraces, but evidence from 2020 supports more conservative management approaches for stable patients with primary spontaneous pneumothorax.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAll patients should receive smoking cessation advice to reduce the risk of recurrence, which is approximately 25% in the first year after primary spontaneous pneumothorax.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Current guidelines support conservative management with observation for stable patients with primary spontaneous pneumothorax regardless of size.","Primary spontaneous pneumothorax occurs in patients without underlying lung disease, whilst secondary occurs in those with pre-existing lung pathology.","Smoking cessation advice should be provided to all patients with spontaneous pneumothorax to reduce recurrence risk."],"references":["Brown SGA, Ball EL, Perrin K, et al. Conservative versus Interventional Treatment for Spontaneous Pneumothorax. N Engl J Med 2020;382:405-15","DeMaio A, Semaan R. Management of Pneumothorax. Clin Chest Med 2021; 42:729\u201338.","Walker S, Hallifax R, Ricciardi S, Fitzgerald D, Keijzers M, Lauk O, Petersen J, Bertolaccini L, Bodtger U, Clive A, Elia S, Froudarakis M, Janssen J, Lee YCG, Licht P, Massard G, Nagavci B, Neudecker J, Roessner E, Van Schil P, Waller D, Walles T, Cardillo G, Maskell N, Rahman N. Joint ERS/EACTS/ESTS clinical practice guidelines on adults with spontaneous pneumothorax. Eur J Cardiothorac Surg. 2024 May 3;65(5):ezae189. doi: 10.1093/ejcts/ezae189. PMID: 38804185.","Antunes G, Neville E, Duffy J, Ali N; Pleural Diseases Group, Standards of Care Committee, British Thoracic Society. BTS guidelines for the management of malignant pleural effusions. Thorax. 2003 May;58 Suppl 2(Suppl 2):ii29-38. doi: 10.1136/thorax.58.suppl_2.ii29. PMID: 12728148; PMCID: PMC1766015."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93675"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"394"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"it